1. while Loop

Used when you don’t know exact number of iterations.

Syntax
while(condition){
    // code
}
Example 1 — Print 1 to 5
int i = 1;

while(i <= 5){
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
Example 2 — Reverse counting
int i = 5;

while(i >= 1){
    System.out.println(i);
    i--;
}
2. do-while Loop

Difference:
👉 It runs at least once, even if condition is false

Syntax
do{
    // code
} while(condition);
Example 1
int i = 1;

do{
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while(i <= 5);
Example 2 (Important)
int i = 10;

do{
    System.out.println(i);
} while(i < 5);

Output:

10

👉 Runs once even though condition is false.

3. while vs for (Important)

Use for loop when:

You know how many times to run

Use while loop when:

You don’t know iterations
Example Comparison

Example 1 (for)

for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++){
    System.out.println(i);
}

Example 2 (while)

int i = 1;
while(i <= 5){
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
4. Loop Control Statements
(A) break → stops loop

Example 1

for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++){
    if(i == 5){
        break;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1 2 3 4
(B) continue → skips iteration

Example 2

for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++){
    if(i == 3){
        continue;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1 2 4 5
